r, and others, the premise of the book is that people shape their ideas of what is permissible, define boundaries of right and wrong, and imagine their sexual worlds through the set of discourses available to them. Dror Ze’evi finds that while some of these discourses were restrictive and others more permissive, all treated sex in its many manifestations as a natural human pursuit. And, he further argues that all these discourses were transformed and finally silenced in the last century, leaving very little to inform Middle Eastern societies in sexual matters. With its innovative approach toward the history of sexuality in the Middle East, Producing Desire sheds new light on the history of the Ottoman Empire, on the history of sexuality and gender, and on the Islamic Middle East today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDesire. 0aSex customszMiddle East. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  aanthropologists.  acultural history.  aeastern societies.  afoucault.  agagnon.  agender studies.  ahistorians.  ahuman nature.  aislamic influence.  alaqueur.  alegal documents.  alust.  amedical texts.  amen and women.  amiddle east history.  amiddle east.  amiddle eastern societies.  amorality.  anonfiction.  aottoman culture.  aottoman empire.  areligious literature.  asex.  asexual desire.  asexual discourse.  asexual history.  asexual thought.  asexuality.  ashadow theater.  atravelogues.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024564840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093898440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938984423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938984/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Back